


It doesn’t support asynchronous logging out of the box.
It doesn’t support rotating files or network sinks.
It’s mostly single-process oriented.

//1. Panic / Expect Safety
//Currently you expect() on locks (Mutex/RwLock). This is fine in controlled apps, but in production:
//Consider returning errors instead of panicking on LOG_CONTEXT or MODULE_LOG_LEVELS locks.
//Example: use unwrap_or_else(|_| { eprintln!("lock poisoned"); return; }) for non-critical logs.

//2. Buffer Size / Memory Limits
//Right now Vec<u8> grows unbounded in memory.
//Consider limiting the buffer size to avoid OOM in long-running apps.
//Could be a ring buffer (VecDeque) or capped Vec<u8> with dropping oldest logs.

3. Async / Non-blocking Writes
Currently, console writes (io::stdout) block threads.
In high-performance apps, consider:
Sending log messages to a dedicated logging thread via crossbeam_channel.
Mutex is lightweight for occasional logs but can be a bottleneck under heavy logging.

//4. Timestamps & Timezones
//You’re using UTC timestamps with chrono. ✅ Good for consistency.
//Optional: allow configurable local time, or human-readable formats in debug mode.

//5. Macro Safety
//Your macros are fine, but note:
//format_args! defers formatting until log is enabled — efficient.
//Ensure module_path!() captures the correct module in nested macros if you add wrappers.

6. File Logging
Currently only supports buffer → file manually.
Optional improvements:
Rolling logs (daily/hourly rotation)
Async flushing to file to avoid blocking main threads

//7. Windows / Terminal Colors
//ANSI works on modern terminals. ✅
//Optional: use console::Term::colorize or colored for future Windows 11+ compatibility if needed.

